=Dunhuang Art=
==Literature==
===PhD Dissertations===
* [[Stanley Abe]]: Mogao Cave 254: A Case Study in Early Chinese Buddhist Art. University of California, 1989
* Janet Baker: The Art of the Sui Dynasty Caves at Dunhuang. University of Kansas, 1991
* [[Ning Qiang]]: Art, Religion and Politics: Dunhuang Cave 220. Harvard University, 1997
* Jennifer McIntire: Visions of Paradise: Sui and Tang Buddhist Pure Land Representations at Dunhuang. Princeton University, 2000
* Michelle Wang: From Dharani to Mandala: A Study of Mogao Cave 14 and Esoteric Buddhist Art of the Tang Dynasty (618-907). Harvard University, 2008
* Karen Hwang: Legitimacy, Genealogy, and the Icon: A Study of Mogao Cave 9, Dunhuang, of the Guiyijun Period (851-1002). Harvard University, 2009
===Monographs===
* Basil Gray: Buddhist Cave Paintings at Tun-huang. London: Faber, 1959
* Alexander Peter Bell: Didactic Narration: Jataka Iconography in Dunhuang with a Catalogue of Jataka Representations in China. Münster: Lit, 2000
* [[Sarah E. Fraser]]: Performing the Visual: The Practice of Buddhist Wall Painting in China and Central Asia, 618-960. Stanford University Press, 2004
* [[Ning Qiang]]: Art, Religion & Politics in Medieval China: The Dunhuang Cave of the Zhai Family. University of Hawai'i Press, 2004
===Articles===
* [[Wu Hung]]: What is Bianxiang? - On The Relationship Between Dunhuang Art and Dunhuang Literature. HJAS 52.1 (1992): 111-192
* [[Sarah E. Fraser]]: Formulas of Creativity: Artist's Sketches and Techniques of Copying at Dunhuang. Artibus Asiae 59.3/4 (2000): 189-224
* [[Sarah E. Fraser]]: An Introduction to the Material Culture of Dunhuang Buddhism: Putting the Object in Its Place. AM 17.1 (2004): [[http://www.ihp.sinica.edu.tw/~asiamajor/pdf/2004a/03%20Fraser.pdf|pdf]]
* Neil Schmid: The Material Culture of Exegesis and Liturgy and a Change in the Artistic Representations in Dunhuang Caves, ca. 700-1000. AM 19.1/2 (2006): 171-210 [[http://www.ihp.sinica.edu.tw/~asiamajor/pdf/2006ab/09%20AM%20vol19%20Schmid.pdf|pdf]]
* Christian Luczanits: Ritual, Instruction and Experiment. Esoteric Drawings from Dunhuang. In: The Art of Central Asia and the Indian Subcontinent. Edited by Anupa Pande. New Dehli: National Museum Institute, 2009: 140-149
* Anupa Pande: Upayakusalya in the Saddharmapundarikasutram. Reflections in the Paintings in Dunhuang. In: The Art of Central Asia and the Indian Subcontinent. Edited by Anupa Pande. New Dehli: National Museum Institute, 2009: 9-15
* Haewon Kim: Meaning of Non-Religious Figures in Vimalakirti Bianxiang in Dunhuang. In: The Art of Central Asia and the Indian Subcontinent. Edited by Anupa Pande. New Dehli: National Museum Institute, 2009: 16-22
